  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">distiller-nf (v0.3.4) is an open-source Nextflow pipeline developed by the open2c consortium for processing Hi-C sequencing data. Deposited on Zenodo with a persistent DOI, the software has accumulated 2,626 views and 287 downloads, and has been cited in three scholarly works \u2014 including a 2025 article in Nature Cell Biology \u2014 signalling genuine uptake within the chromosome biology community.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">distiller-nf is a Nextflow-based workflow tool designed to streamline the alignment, filtering, and contact-pair generation steps central to Hi-C and related chromatin conformation capture experiments. The pipeline is maintained under the open2c umbrella \u2014 a collaborative effort bringing together researchers from institutions including the Institute of Molecular Biotechnology, the University of Massachusetts Chan Medical School, and MIT, alongside contributors such as Paolo Di Tommaso, a key figure in the broader Nextflow ecosystem. The software is openly licensed and version-tracked across more than ten archived releases on Zenodo, underscoring a sustained commitment to reproducibility and long-term accessibility.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Citation evidence, though modest in raw count, is notably high in quality. All three recorded citations appeared recently \u2014 two in 2024 and one in 2025 \u2014 and span both active preprints on bioRxiv and a peer-reviewed article in Nature Cell Biology. That Nature Cell Biology paper, which examines how interphase chromosome conformation is established through programmes inherited across mitosis or through the cytoplasm, lists Sergey Venev (a distiller-nf contributor) as a co-author, suggesting the pipeline was integral to the underlying data processing. Geoffrey Fudenberg appears as a citing author across two separate works, including a bioRxiv preprint on the physical chemistry of interphase loop extrusion \u2014 a conceptually adjacent area where robust Hi-C data processing is essential.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The citing institutions span academic research environments in the United States, with contributions from the University of Southern California, the Stowers Institute for Medical Research, and Howard Hughes Medical Institute, among others. This profile is consistent with a specialist but well-regarded tool embedded in active 3D genome research programs. The software's role as upstream infrastructure means it typically receives citation credit indirectly, making even three explicit citations a meaningful indicator of real-world adoption. The versioned release history further reflects a living codebase rather than a one-time deposit.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">From a stewardship perspective, distiller-nf benefits from Zenodo's DOI-based versioning system, with the concept DOI aggregating all releases and individual version DOIs enabling precise reproducibility. The repository is openly accessible with no usage restrictions, and the source code is mirrored on GitHub. Taken together, the combination of high-visibility citations, sustained download activity, and robust archival infrastructure positions distiller-nf as a reliable, community-vetted component of the Hi-C data analysis toolkit.</p>",
